## Vercel Web Analytics Installation

Successfully installed and configured Vercel Web Analytics for this Next.js project following the official Vercel documentation.

### Changes Made

**1. Package Installation:**
- Added `@vercel/analytics` v2.0.1 to project dependencies
- Updated package-lock.json to reflect new dependency

**2. Code Changes:**
- Modified `src/app/layout.tsx` to integrate Vercel Analytics:
  - Imported `Analytics` component from `@vercel/analytics/next`
  - Added `<Analytics />` component inside the `<body>` tag of the root layout

### Implementation Details

This Next.js project uses the App Router with TypeScript. Following the official Vercel Analytics quickstart guide (https://vercel.com/docs/analytics/quickstart), I:

1. Fetched the latest documentation to ensure using up-to-date installation instructions
2. Identified the project as Next.js App Router based on the presence of `app/layout.tsx`
3. Installed the package using npm (the project's package manager)
4. Added the Analytics component to the root layout file, placing it at the end of the body tag to ensure it loads after the main content
5. Preserved existing code structure including font configurations, metadata, and styling

### Verification

- ✅ Build completed successfully with no errors
- ✅ Linter passed with no issues
- ✅ TypeScript compilation successful
- ✅ All static pages generated correctly (9 routes)

### Next Steps

After deploying to Vercel:
1. Enable Web Analytics in the Vercel dashboard under the project's Analytics section
2. Verify analytics tracking by checking the browser's Network tab for requests to `/_vercel/insights/*`
3. Visitor data will begin appearing in the Vercel Analytics dashboard

### Files Modified

- `package.json` - Added @vercel/analytics dependency
- `package-lock.json` - Updated with new dependency tree
- `src/app/layout.tsx` - Added Analytics component import and integration
